the idl/generated folder empty.

documents.

comments.message: Lgtm.  Needs a CI update to resolve the tests, since the baseline for comparison will be moving.
If it is empty, should we consider removing the folder? Or is it needed temporarily during the build?
Since we don't know what else will be generated by QTI's idl tool in the future so I think it's better to leave them like that.
The empty folder will just disappear through the magic of git anyway - deleting all the files from the folder is deleting the folder.
Is this wording confusing, considering we are saying we are discontinuing the docx up above?

@Giang, we could do it now or as a separate change, but since we're "breaking" the CI build here anyway, we could run the build and commit the outcome now, too.  Then the repo is populated with the expected outcome as a baseline for the next changes and CI updates.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-66 - Long TX/RX format fields be swapped to work with HSW

HSW current deployment interprets these data as RX then TX order
which contradicts with QMIIDL and FW's order. Since the next HSW
release cycle will be for while, so QMIIDL and FW should adapt to
HSW's field order.

Since this implementation is the first use by the HSW team, it
is acceptable for this TLV change to stay with the current
TLV minor version.

Change-Id: I1d19974b410fa32d83fe0e69bb071120fbf36c42
commits.subject: QMIIDL-66 - Long TX/RX format fields be swapped to work with HSW

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-65 - Support multiple configurations for GET AUTO-SIM list

This change allows to return variable size configurations
for AUTO-SIM GET command, one PRI_IIN group list per one
configuration at a time.

This change doesn't require an increase in the IDL minor version
because the object is still in the first time integraton phase.

Resolves: QMIIDL-65
Change-Id: Id6e31bea0ec2a74c98c35b2d4ac922000fd11dab
commits.subject: QMIIDL-65 - Support multiple configurations for GET AUTO-SIM list

comments.message: Changes look good to me. One question I have is how did we determine 32 is enough?

One question.
Is it OK that the data type in swi_dms_get_auto_sim_list_resp_msg_v01 do not match with AT response?

For example, in AT!IMSIM? response, the attributes look like:
IIN 89** -1 1 PRI
PLMN **:* -1 1 PRI

In AT response, the <type> and <source> are converted to a string formation and the <rank> is displayed as signed integer.
Whereas in swi_dms_get_auto_sim_list_resp_msg_v01, <type>, <rank>, and <source> are in uint8.
Need to re-size swi_dms_get_auto_sim_list_resp_msg_v01 which uses 78,924 bytes (it could be more after byte alignment)
AT has everything expressed in text string, QMI has a luxury to use primitive types.
This looks like exceed max msg_len. Could you double check?

OK, let's implement a little protocol to return the max configuration along with an index. 

We also need similar mechanism for PRI_IIN entry.

I think we don't need this index. It is better to return the complete list of one configuration. Besides, it is very difficult to handle the attribs list one by one in modem side.
So each GET response returns one carrier configuration with the completed list of entries.
What do you think?

As we don't want to predict and "over-reserve" the memory heap so I limit the attribs list to 20 only, but it looks like we have no choice than reserving 100 and then not serving more than 100 entries of the list...

If the modem can handle list index query in some manners, that would be best, though.

Okay, agreed.
Let's go for the conclusion per our side discussion

Per offline discussion, we will support up to 50 PRI_IIN entries in a list (this limit should be used to control at!imsim SET command as well). This will allow straightforward implementation on QMI AUTO_SIM GET. In the future, when we have a need to support more than 50, we will have to release a new FW to utilize list_group_index and max_list_group_count. 

For the time being, list_group_index shall be 0 and max_list_group_count shall be 1.

Done.

When carrier name is specified (carrier_valid=1), this config_index will be inapplicable.
Is that right?

Do we agree that the GET command returns one carrier config at a time and that users need to manage their apps to obtain a full list of carrier sim matching list one by one?

It looks good to me. Thank you!
Do we agree to have this name change to 'max_config_count'?
Do we agree to change this name to 'max_config_count'?
Patch 7 should have it all. Thanks.

Looks OK to me.
Just minor comments.
This value starts from '1', should be clearly documented in QMI interface specification
Done. This value is returned by the modem's service. And it could be > 1 in the future.
This value starts from '0', should be clearly documented in QMI interface specification
Done. This value is returned by the modem's service. So it's better that the Host just follows whichever value that the modem returns. Hence, I don't think we need to document this.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-63 - Include missing LPM voters within QMI_DMS_SWI_GET_PC_INFO

Added the following PC clients to lpmflags within
QMI_DMS_SWI_GET_PC_INFO_RESP:
bit6: RF Calibration
bit7: MMW Calibration
bit8: RFC Initialization

supportedlpmflags has additionally been added to advertise which PC
clients are supported on the given platform.

Resolves: QMIIDL-63
Change-Id: I6f40632ee714e122b4148a70f32869d7b730dfcb
Signed-off-by: Grayson Halliday <GHalliday@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-63 - Include missing LPM voters within QMI_DMS_SWI_GET_PC_INFO

comments.message: it is problematic from a compatibility perspective if we are changing the meaning of a bit.

Hi Kevin,

Bit 6 (RFCAL) is not listed within the QMI spec as being used, nor is it set within	QMI_DMS_SWI_GET_PC_INFO_RESP. The combination of these two factors led me to believe its inclusion within this .idl file was accidental.
I did a bit of digging and see that it is used in the MDM9x50 (EM75xx) version of swiqmi_dms.c. Can we rearrange them bit6 can be compatible with 9x50?
Good catch. I will include this within the next patchset.

Just a minor comment/concern, but not really specific to this change:  As we add flags, the documentation isn't clear on whether all flags are supported by all firmware, but it would likely be assumed that if RFCAL is clear, then RFCAL vote is not asserted.  This wouldn't be true on older firmware.  Maybe we should add to the documentation that this is an informative message and that the client needs to be aware that the software may not support all flags in the message.

Maybe it would be enough to add "(Added in 1.11)" in the documentation for the new flags.  Maybe someone has a better idea though.  The more QMI oriented method might be new TLVs for new flags, instead of using the "Reserved" section, but what we've done here was definitely the plan.
As discussed offline with Paul, supportedlpmflags has been added to indicate which clients are supported by the given platform.
Just a question on how to document the absense of the optional TLV, but I think the implementation looks good.  Thanks
As per offline discussions with Ryan, the added TLV should be moved to the end of the QMI object.
Looks good, but don't give me any credit for this, you noticed this one :)  Good catch.

Would it be correct or necessary to describe what it means when this TLV is not provided?  Something to the effect of "If this TLV is not provided, or prior to service version 1.11, bits 0-6 of lpmflags are assumed to be supported."  Alternatively, this should only be happening in < 1.11 implementations, and clients should look at older specs for that.  Unfortunately we don't actually provide our specs that we, unfortunately.
I don't think it would hurt to include. I'll include the change in the next patchset.
This field is not changed, so its version should be still 1.1. It's ok to add new value meaning without changing the version.
Will update name as per the comment here - https://gerrit.legato/c/sierra-mdm/+/79995/comment/f04057dd_59078258/.
Bitmask definitions now match client names within pcpm.c

I think it would be good to add more sentences below to describe each mask.
Hopefully it won't look too ugly in the Word doc.

    bit0: W_DISABLE - W_DISABLE pin
    bit1: User - Host interface
    bit2: Temp - Low/High Temperature
    bit3: Volt - Low/High Voltage
    bit4: BIOS - BIOS Locking feature
    bit5: IMSWITCH - Image Preference mismatch
    bit6: RFCAL - RF Calibration missing
    bit7: MMWCAL - MM Calibration missing
    bit8: RFC_INIT - RF init failure.

We should also add a note that not all bit masks are supported by each product. "See supportedlpmflags for more information."

Hi Paul,

I can add the descriptions within the .idl file. However, the word doc already lists descriptions for each LPM voter under the "Optional TLVs" table. Given the width of the "Description" column, we may want to keep the word doc text as-is. 
Unless there is a rule that the doc text must match the .idl file text?

Ah, right. I forgot about that section of the doc.
Can we add that text into the IDL file, instead of my above suggestion?

Looks like you added my suggestion above. I was thinking of adding the text in the word doc to the IDL file.
If and when the word doc is deprecated, we'll lose a bunch of information.
Unless we are planning to do a final sync between the IDL file and word doc before it gets deprecated. -- A question for Giang and Ryan.

Sorry, it appears I misunderstood the request.
By "that text" I assumed you still meant the text within the suggestion, and that "instead of my above suggestion" referred to including it only within the .idl file and not the word doc.
I can upload a new patchset including the word doc descriptions if need be.
I say let's go with copying the word doc text here. However, I think it would have to be in a separate section as opposed next to the bit mask?

It appears that in other .idl files, some QMI objects contain @DESCRIPTION sections with additional details. However, it appears some add this directly after the @BRIEF, whereas some add it below the message definition.
Is it known which location is correct?

@Paul, to your previous question, we will need to perform a large scale sync-up before deprecating the word doc, since this theme would apply to many objects.  But I think it's a good idea to catch as much as possible here too, like you've asked for, just to keep that gap as small as possible, within reason.

Looks good to me.
Just a forward looking comment. More for Giang and Ryan to answer.

Giang/Ryan, can we merge and tag this change?
Thanks,
Paul

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-60 - Support READ and WRITE AUTO-SIM list

Add QMI objects for the customers to update/manage
their AUTO-SIM list to easily enable their SIM to
operate with new carrier's network configuration
without re-certifying the product.

Resolves: QMIIDL-60
Change-Id: I0a7ff5dde3b1619255eb94ab0a124a16ee790a2a
commits.subject: QMIIDL-60 - Support READ and WRITE AUTO-SIM list

comments.message: No service is being added - only defining messages to already existing QMI service (SWIDMS)
Should these be +1 to include a NUL? If not, documentation should state that a NUL must not be included.
When string type is used in idl, the generated *.h file will have a [+ 1] for the corresponding char array.

This arbitrary carrier name size limit is not adequate to capture all carrier names. For example Telefonica, or Vodafone would not work. This should be a variable length TLV, with max length of 255. The implementation would either rely on the length or document that a NUL terminated string is needed.
Good point, I will increase this to 255. Done
Not sure what this is supposed to contain?

This is equivalent to configuration field returned by AT!IMSIM? It displays the PRI and FW version like:

GENERIC_002.023_000, Firmware: 01.11.00.00

So I added explanation
  //! Configuration in the form of "<PRIID>, Firmware: <revision>".
Under what conditions would this message be present in the response?

I will change this to mandatory as this field should always come along with an associated configuration.

For un-provisioned product, the QMI itself shall return QMI_ERR_NOT_PROVISIONNED.

Do we intend to keep this restricted to Level 2 access only? I am not sure how that would work from QMI, but it would seem we need to have some restrictions otherwise this QMI message gives full access to what AT!IMSIM is restricting.

We don't have restricted QMI. Maybe we can start thinking about linking the access level to AT LOCK status or start introducing a global QMI_UNLOCK SET/GET like AT.

On the other notes, AT!IMSIM is level 1 protection, so this QMI object should follow that model.
AT!IMSIM only allows query for Level 1. Any modifications require Level 2, and if we are to follow AT!IMSIM then the QMI object needs to implement some kind of write protection.
As discussed, this is a bigger scope that requires a complete design of QMI GET/SET/OPEN LOCK and lock status management per QMI client instance.
Documentation here should be self explanatory and specific to QMI interface only, rather than pointing to an AT command.
It's a common practice and sometimes useful to relate these 2 in QMI documentation.
These will appear in the documentation so perhaps just use the QMI_SWI_DMS_* defines. In the implementation of these objects we can have a GLOBAL_ASSERT() to ensure they are aligned with NV.

Can the source be part of the swi_dms_auto_sim_attributes_type or perhaps define a new structure to contain both the source and attribs? This way no index matching would be needed to obtain the source corresponding to the attributes.

Source will only come in the response so it is a common practice to have these types of field being on a separated item. Furthermore, it might be confusing to have another similar structure in the include file.

I understand the part about not wanting source in the request, but it seems like it could be a little more intuitive to have source and the attributes struct in a single struct for a single response TLV.  Then the advantage of defining an attributes struct for req and resp is still maintained, but the parsing is a little more straight forward, at least arguably.  We can then also make that TLV optional, so that when querying a carrier with no data, we can return SUCCESS, with PRI and FWVER, and an empty response list.
Should this delete entries only added by QMI_SWI_DM_SET_AUTO_SIM?
This might be clear, but where does the client find the full list of carrier names, so that they don't stumble on ATT versus AT&T for example?

Oh, it's a top secret to share the list of supported carriers to the user... Just kidding.

But I think this could be quickly figured out by the Host team during the coding time to pass in the right value.

If we want to return the carrier name list programatically, this would be a separate work that provide support for both AT and QMI.

As a relatively new feature, just wondering if there's any value in making response elements optional?  Mandatory, and later pointless (if we end up with a new idea) could make these a nuisance that we need to include but ignore, based on newer TLVs with better data.  

I don't actually have an idea for what the "better" data would be, but this comes up occasionally in other messages.

Could we clarify the reply if there is no entry for the requested carrier?  I assume it's an error of some type, ommiting the mandatory fields.

Normally, for a new object, all fields tend to be mostly mandatory to affirm to the world that we understand perfectly the nature of the data we return. 

Furthermore, for this particular object, I don't see that we can omit any field, even in the future. So, it's good to have an affirmative specification here...

You have a good point about clarifying that we would return QMI_ERR if specified carrier is invalid or has empty list.
I'm fine with all the replies so +1 from me.

QMIIDL-62 - Update QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_SCC_RX_INFO to support multiple SCC cells

Description:
This QMI command was originally implemented to report the RX information
for only one SCC. The changes will report the RX information for all the
Secondary Secondary Cells (up to 7CC LTE CA).

Resolves: QMIIDL-62
Related: QTIX5510-3124
Change-Id: Ic7305abed736a19801df571f6d33ce04919870c2
Signed-off-by: brgao <brgao@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-62 - Update QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_SCC_RX_INFO to support multiple SCC cells

comments.message:
We cannot change content like this. We should create another TLV to deliver the correct contents.

These kinds of type mismatch should have been caught in AMSS compilation warning and I think we should pay close attention to these warning when creating QMIIDL objects to avoid re-edition like this in the future.
Hi Giang Do-Tien, I have removed the changes of IDL structure content's type, thanks for your comments.
Thanks for taking time to review the codes and provide very good comments and suggestions, Bruce
This should be 12 with the newly added TLV.
Yes, I will change that, thanks.
You are right, I will make the changes, thanks.
I have made the changes, thanks
Will this always be filled with SCCI[0]? If so, please add to the line.
Yes, the RX information is for SCCI[0], will add the comment for that.
Please add "when there are multiple SCCs." to the line.
Yes, Will change that, thanks for pointing it out.
Looks good. Just very minor comment (that I forgot to reply from last review).

Hi Bruce and Giang,
Minor comments below.
Otherwise looks good to me.
Regards,
Paul
Hi Paul, I will take a look, thanks for your comments.
Thank you very much for taking time to review the code change and provide the valuable comments and suggestions, Bruce

Hi Bruce and Giang,
Minor comment below. Feel free to modify or merge the change.
Thanks,
Paul

Is the convention to use "_len"? If so, then that is OK.
Otherwise, using "instances" seemed fairly intuitive.
When I think if "len", I think more in terms of how many bytes are to follow.
"array_len" is also a good.
Hi Paul, yes, it is the convention to use "_len", thanks for your comment.
I would prefer rx_chain_info_array_len, to match scci_rx_info_array_len.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-59 - Support for long TX and RX channel format

LTE TX and RX channel is of type uint32 but our existing
TX channel is only of type uint16. Create an optional long
channel type to support the full length for both TX and RX
channel.

Legacy channel fields will be capped at 65535 in overflown case.

Resolves: QMIIDL-59
Change-Id: I88cc45cc11d5b2cf8decd61682b8bec5c5f789c7

It is decided that when any of the channel is capped then both channels will be reported in long format as well.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-57 - Update QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_CA_CELL_INFO to return Tx info

Description:
The current QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_CA_CELL_INFO response doesn't include
the Tx channel information for each CC.

Solution:
Update QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_CA_CELL_INFO response to include Tx channel
information for each CC

Resolves: QMIIDL-57
Change-Id: I9a947a6201610f18c5cd177a79a19befbdbf9abe

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-55 - Revise QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_ANTENNA_SIG_INFO for mmw antennas

Description:
Customer requests to extend the QMI response message to cover not only
rssi, but also rsrp, rsrq and sinr for mmw antennas.

Solution:
Add the mmw_sig_info TLV(0x17) at the end of the QMI response message.
This check-in also modifies the name of the parameters from
rx*_sig_info_available to rx*_sig_info_valid for syncing up with the
latest QMI IFS specification.

Resolves: QMIIDL-55 QTIX5510-3065
Change-Id: I80fa8e27cdcce865ad307c3270a5cf12c30d50b5
Signed-off-by: Kenneth Yeung <kyeung@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-55 - Revise QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_ANTENNA_SIG_INFO for mmw antennas

comments.message: Hi Giang, Can you review and push this review forward?

Hi Giang,
Can you review and push the review forward?
Thanks,
Paul

Looks fine to me.  The name change of parameters is actually not a good practice even though the binary stays the same, since some dependant code could be using the previous names, and now fail to build (we used to see this with Legato, in which case they would now need two code paths to build the two variants).  But since I assume we haven't used these yet, it's not a practical problem.  Could you just mention that in the commit message?  Something to the effect of "Parameter name change to sync-up with late specification updates affects messages that have not yet been implemented, and so no compatibility issue is expected." 

This just explains the situation to future readers that might wonder why they're asked not to change parameter names.

As a follow-up, I see that those older parameter names are implemented, but only for one modem which is being updated concurrently.  That still seems fine but worth mentioning to account for the general "rule" breaking.

Thanks for your review.  I have revised the commit message.  Sorry I didn't realize the impact of changing variables name. I just thought that "valid" was more appropriate to "available" as the later one imply that the subsequent parameters would be absent if "available=false", and this is not really true.

I will avoid doing this in the future.

What exactly is Antenna Group 0 and Antenna Group 1? In low-power mmWave scenarios, we have one mmWave antenna module active. In high-power mmWave CPE devices, we have all four antenna modules active. I'm struggling to understand how the antenna groups map to those scenarios.

Each of the two antenna groups refer either the combined horizontal polarization antennas or the combined vertical polarization antennas.  Depending on the direction of observation, it may be obscure to determine whether it is horizontal/ vertical.  It is therefore more appropriate to just use AG0 or AG1.
If I understand correctly, each antenna module has many small antennas and each of them are designed to send and receive RF signal on either the horizontal / vertical plane.

You may read the following for more details:

https://issues.sierrawireless.com/browse/FERRARI-1611?focusedCommentId=7915893&page=com.atlassian.jira.plugin.system.issuetabpanels:comment-tabpanel#comment-7915893

https://qualcomm-cdmatech-support.my.salesforce.com/5004V000015i6Kc?srPos=0&srKp=500
In that case, how do we handle high power CPE when four mmWave antenna modules may be active at one time? Do we need to define AG0-1, AG1-1, AG0-2, AG1-2, AG0-3, AG1-3, AG0-4, and AG1-4?

In the last log taken by Sam when 4 hi-power mmWave antenna modules were used, I could only see two signal info (one for AG0 and one for AG1) available from the log.  That verified what QTI claimed that these info were aggregated (or combined) signal info from either plane.

What is the maximum number of groups that we could have supported? Should we  use optional nas_swi_mmw_sig_info_type mmw_sig_info<QMI_NAS_SWI_MAX_ANT_GROUP> and then remove the notion of grp# in the nas_swi_mmw_sig_info_type?

In our last testing, there are only 2 groups of signal info even all eight IF connections are attached to the QTM antenna boards.  That is why we now call it "Antenna Group 0 or 1". Group 0 / group 1 can either correspond to the vertical or horizontal polarization and both groups are always present.  I will confirm about it after the test result.  Therefore there is no rush to merge the change.
There are only two antenna groups.
No other comments from me, looks good.  CI results look good too.

I think we should restrain ourselves from changing the structure's field like adding/removing/renaming field as the minor version increase does not apply to this type of change. Minor version increase is needed when adding optional field. Luckily, in our case, the type is unchanged so it is binary compatible. I prefer keeping 1.9 though.

Hi Giang, can you merge this ticket, I don't have permissions to merge into sierra-qmi-idl.
I'm going to remove the topic field so that each ticket can be submitted individually.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-54 - DEVRC QMI configuration

Adding QAPI messages for configuring DEVRC. The QAPI message is
equivalent to AT+DRCC. Configuration message consists of a mandatory
operation TLV, indicating if it is a read (0) or a write (1) operation.
All other fields are optional, but ignored if the operation TLV is read.
The response contains an optional structure that is only present if the
operation was read.

Change-Id: Ie0330d685fdd1b038ef4926bbfa4f4b33b83b70e
commits.subject: QMIIDL-54 - DEVRC QMI configuration

comments.message: Hi Stoyan, still looks good functionally, but just requesting some additional IDL format documentation for the generated HTML, to help describe some usages.

Here and maybe elsewhere, it would be good to add a little more documentation to describe what happens if request is "Read" and optionals are provided, or explicitly state that omitted optionals are untouched in the write operation.
Similarly, please document the behaviour for a write response, for example, so that expectations are clear.
Done - See added IDL comment on line 1089 - 1092

Thanks - the second comment didn't actually show up in the HTML, but when I review the HTML, there are lots of flaws.  Let's leave it as-is and come back to it when we have time to improve the documentation.  I took a stab at fixing it too, but I couldn't get it after about 10 minutes and a quick review of the syntax.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-53 - Revise QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_ANTENNA_SIG_INFO for sub6 antennas

Description:
Customer requests to extend the QMI response message to cover not only
rssi, but also rsrp, rsrq and sinr for all antennas.

Solution:
Add the lte_sig_info TLV(0x15) and sub6_sig_info TLV (0x16) at the end
of the QMI response message.

Resolves: QMIIDL-53 QTIX5510-3026
Change-Id: Ib0e66bac9ff2163b79c112a0fbcff0c741adc24d
Signed-off-by: Kenneth Yeung <kyeung@sierrawireless.com>

comments.message:
Hi Kenneth,

Some comments about the spec version and comments added in-line.  Some of the comments might require minor changes in the doc review as well.

Thanks,
Ryan

Thanks Ryan's comment and I have replied.
Before changing the code, can I have a clear guidance what to do with the versioning?

I'm not sure exactly how we make use of the version in a service extension, but this would need to be the next highest value I think.  I see some use of 1.7 at the top of this file, so this would be 1.8 (I think - but we also list version 2.2 in our 4110880, section 2.2), despite the current revision in the file being 0, and the document still showing , The version info in the new TLVs should match.

We would also need to increase the revision at the top of the file to match.  The "revision" value is the minor rev.

You have opened up a fundamental question;

Does this version represent a "global" version of the QMI API or does it represent a version of a particular message?
The highest version in this file is 2.2. See QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_SCC_RX_INFO.  So, should I be using 2.3 above?
In the QMI doc, there has been rare instance that people filled in the "Version Last modified" as the same as the QMI doc revision.  See "3.3.4.2	QMI_WDS_SWI_GET_3GPP_CFG_ITEM _RESP". And the IDL code follows it.  The QMI doc version is now V3.41.  Many people have not been following such practice for a long time as the highest version I can find in all IDL files is "@VERSION 3.1".

My opinion is to keep that version as the version of a particular message.  The global API version we communicate outside should be the QMIIDL tag that can be mentioned in the QMI doc somewhere. (Beware that sometimes we tag the firmware in between two QMIIDL tags!)

May I have a clear guidance about how I should fill the version info going forward?
Done. Thanks for the suggestion. Agreed to follow the original Qualcomm way of using the "revision".
Since this is used to generate the doc, it would be good to put "rxp" and others into words.
The comments from the doc for each field should be in here, since this is meant to generate the HTML docs to replace the Word docs, eventually.
I don't think the version has any meaning in the struct, since the struct can't change across versions, and the TLV itself has a version in the message.
I see many people "version" all the fields inside a struct.  I guess the benefit is that we can tell which field is newly changed if a struct is changed later.

Fair enough, and I suppose they aren't technically inaccurate.  I don't know how we could change the meaning or content of a struct without violating compatibility in the spec, so I don't expect these could ever change.  Maybe an enum could be extended and that change to the spec would be valid, I suppose.
We should add comments to indicate that these TLVs replace the older TLVs, and why, for the generated documentation.

Thanks Kenneth, changes look good to me.  As a standalone spec change, this passes verification too, so we can override the -1 verification vote if necessary, since that relies on changes outside QMIIDL.
Ryan or Giang, can you approve and merge the changes?
The topic needs to be removed to merge, since the rest of the topic isn't ready to submit yet.
I don't have permission to remove the topic. But I changed the topic in the other review. This review can be merged now.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-52 - New SWINAS objects for RF Device Status and mmWave Config

Two QMI objects are added as following:
1. QMI_SWINAS_GET_RFDEV_STATUS
This QMI object is to get the RF device status during power up.

2. QMI_SWINAS_MMWAVE_CONFIG
This QMI object is to set mmWave RFC to configure or disable mmWave
functionality.

These commands can be used in combination to diagnose and/or disable
problematic RFFE components.

Resolves: QMIIDL-52
Related: QTIX5510-2685 FERRARI-907
Signed-off-by: brgao <brgao@sierrawireless.com>
Change-Id: I0d447649bbae29957f1a098ff36dcf55e1f481b9

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-23 - Introduce QAPI_APPS_VERSION_READ

This new object will replace the misleading QAPI_LEGATO_VERSION_READ
as these objects are not handled by Legato.

It returns subsystem name field and version string field of each
subsystem component relevant to the APPS side.

It won't return the fields for unapplicable subsystem.

It will return the version info of all subsystems if no specific version
type is specified in the query.

Change-Id: I022ed716d77e5d8e3c6215fab2e30573962bb888
commits.subject: QMIIDL-23 - Introduce QAPI_APPS_VERSION_READ

comments.message: Can we document that this would be used for ThreadX version?  I think the choice, judging from the implementation file, is logical but I'm not sure that it's obvious.
After offline discussion, I will rename these to DATA_APPS_xyz_VER_ID.

To make the usage simpler, can the version types be returned in different TLVs, and then another request type added for ALL?  For example, request type 0 returns TLV 0x10.  Request type 1 returns TLV 0x11, etc... and request type 0xFF (for example) returns TLVs 0x10 through 0x16 (i.e. all of them).

It is more complex to return different TLV for each single query based on different id. I think returning the same TLV for each single query is more straightforward.

For returning ALL versions, I was attempting to make the id field optional TLV and when it is not specified it means ALL, but this requires more memory management logic in the code, so I am reluctant to support that feature (although I was the one wanting to offer this initially).

It sounds like there was some miscommunication on this.  This is now almost the same as the Legato labeled message, except for the subsystem name field, which is only needed for ATI8 and wasn't really part of the problem description for this.  I don't think as currently constructed this change would offer enough benefit to warrant breaking compatibility between modem and apps (i.e. new modem would stop working with old apps, unless we support both messages).  We could add an optional TLV for the subsystem name to the Legato message and not break compatibility.  Currently the solution wouldn't solve the problem statement from the ticket.

After some offline discussion, we agree that I will support optional version_type to return all available subsystem (instead of mandatory), data_qapi will parse/translate these 2 fields into the pre-allocated string provided by data_qapi_remote_get_all's caller.

The code is simpler this way for the object, and in the handler I suspect, but this means we need to presently predict the max size of this, and create an object large enough now, which creates some overhead - space for 13 yet undefined subsystem strings ~ 3.5KB.  If we add a TLV for each type, we can add new TLVs later, and we don't need to allocate any excess now, although there's a small overhead for the "TL" each time.

QMIIDL-43 - Add new QAPI messages for accessing the status of the atlock diag

Description:
Add new QAPI messages for apss to access the status of atlock diag from mpss

Root cause:
New requirement

Solution:
Add new qmi message as below:
- QAPI_ATLOCK_DIAG_OP_REQ
- QAPI_ATLOCK_DIAG_OP_RESP

Change-Id: I9ccd32e585899f988c7c38d0c2986e9e79b10071
Signed-off-by: Ellis Huang <ehuang@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-43 - Add new QAPI messages for accessing the status of the atlock diag

comments.message: qapi_status should only be used as the first field for RESP message.
Is this really needed for a request?
Although, it could be used to deliver the unlock status, but from the code, I see that the unlock status seems to be delivered via qapi_status. Some clarifications are needed here.
Why do we need this field for the request command?
The name "Result Code" sounds better for this field.

It's good to specify the meaning of the numerical value using const xyz = ... so that these xyz will be defined in qapi_common_v01.h which can be seen by the C files so that we don't need to change atudefs.h for this.

Not sure if it is more optimal for the request message to have no argument and the response would be a status that is either AT_LOCKED (==1) or AT_LOW_UNLOCKED (==2) or AT_HIGH_UNLOCKED (==3)? This allows to get the actual lock status with one QMI call.

Hi Giang,

Agree. Actually, I considered the way you mentioned, but the current implementation followed the method modem used for the consistency.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-50 - Fix compile error for macro redefinition

The Qualcomm NAS service extension and Sierra NAS service defined a Service ID
constant with the same name.  The result, if both headers are included, is a
macro redefinition error on QMI_SERVICE_SWI_NAS_ID.  This change eliminates the
naming collision by hardcoding the Qualcomm NAS service extension ID, following
the example present in the parent NAS service, and reflecting the intent that
this value is not expected to be referenced directly by clients.

Resolves: QMIIDL-50 QTI9X07-5050
Change-Id: Ib661173374e69ca450127017f020abf3076a9c11
commits.subject: QMIIDL-50 - Fix compile error for macro redefinition

" not working here?  Are we dealing with an imperfect copy?  If it's defined as 0x3 in another location, then that location is wrong, if I'm understanding correctly.  But this _is_ qmiidl/api/swiqmi_swinas_v01.h, so I'm not quite understanding the comment in the commit message.

Patch Set 1:

It's a name collision.  Our Qualcomm NAS service extension and our custom Sierra NAS service both named their service ID "QMI_SERVICE_SWI_NAS_ID" in the IDL files.  This has never come up before I guess, but should be easy to resolve without workarounds.

commits.commitMessage:
swinas: Fix compile error for macro redefinition

When compiling with LE.2.1.2 headers, the following error shows:
.../proprietary/qct/wp76xx/inc/services/swiqmi_swinas_v01.h:83:
   error: "QMI_SERVICE_SWI_NAS_ID_V01" redefined [-Werror]
   83 | #define QMI_SERVICE_SWI_NAS_ID_V01 0xFC

This happens due to the macro being previously defined with value
0x3 in file qmiidl/api/swiqmi_swinas_v01.h.

Wrap macro redefinition with #ifdef guards.

Resolves: QTI9x07-5050
Change-Id: Ib33c6710332cc5420d42753bcc14a774a9020b5c
Signed-off-by: Zoran Markovic <zmarkovic@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: swinas: Fix compile error for macro redefinition

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-47 - Add new QMI object for blocking diag commands from APPS

Description:
Add new QMI object to block diag commands

Root cause:
New requirement.

Solution:
Add IDL definition for QMI_SWI_DMS_SET_BLOCK_DIAG_COMMANDS.
- QMI_SWI_DMS_SET_BLOCK_DIAG_COMMANDS_REQ
- QMI_SWI_DMS_SET_BLOCK_DIAG_COMMANDS_RESP

Resolves: LXSWIX55-319 QMIIDL-47
Change-Id: I88e02d81559fd08dc9c28243bca0bfa6c4637d65
Signed-off-by: Jarvis Wang <JaWang@sierrawireless.com>

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-48 - Add new QMI object to get LTE UE config

Issue Description:
According to SA team's request,
we need to add  QMI object to get LTE UE Config info (CA enable) corresponding to response of AT command AT!RATCA.

Root Cause:
According to SA team's request,
we need to add  QMI object to get LTE UE Config info (CA enable) corresponding to response of AT command AT!RATCA.

Solution:
Add SWI QMI QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_LTE_UE_CONFIG object.

Change-Id: I763fd1b546b50348c9c7defc1d099a50373b7310
Signed-off-by: Zipeng Sun <zsun@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-48 - Add new QMI object to get LTE UE config

comments.message: is it possible to have more than 4 rx paths in the spec? If so, perhaps we should structure this QMI so it is expandable in the future.
We got NR5G cell info  from a configure signaling message. The message can support 4 rx paths at most. For now in the SWI's products, the rx paths will not be more than 4.

Yes, understood that we currently don't have any product with more than 4 paths. But in future if we did an 8 path product (for example), then this object would need to be reworked. Are we ok with that? Or should we try to make the object more expandable?

I think it is better not to expand the object for further compatibility. For we do not know how many rx paths(8?16?32?64) will be in the future. May be there will be more elements added in the object to provide carrier infomation. Or the formulas will be changed. We can keep track with the QC's design.
remove leading spaces (occurs other places below too)

Should be 1.0 (as v01.idl defines the major number and revision 0 defines the minor number).

For other existing objects and TLVs, we will have to decide later whether we want to realign them correctly or not. But let's do it right from now on.
Here and in several places, looks like maybe a character conversion issue.
The comments differ for each struct - I think it would be good to consistently provide details, assuming this same comment is true in each case.

In my opinion, the version of filed "mandatory qmi_response_type resp" is match to the "nas qmi service" rather than the "1.1.1	QMI_NAS_SWI_GET_ANTENNA_SIG_INFO". Notice that version of the "mandatory qmi_response_type resp" is 1.1 in this idl. Shall I change this version from 1.1 to 1.0? Please help to check.

To be correct, it should be the same version number with other TLVs that are introduced at this time...

It's ugly either way. The best compromise fix would be:
1. Determine the biggest minor version number used in this idl that is with major version 1 (I believe it is 7 for 1.7 in nas_swi_ind_register_req_msg) 
2. This new QMI object will be then on version 1.8
3. Change revision 0; to revision 8;

This doesn't fix the objects that are declared with version 2.2, which I think should be declared with 1.x to be correct for v01.idl

This requires a corresponding change in QMI SWI NAS docx (probably can be done with 3.37 review by Zipeng).
I haven't seen any correction related to VERSION number.
Hi Giang, you should  check the modification in patch 8. Thanks.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-37 - Add build option to disable messages from an input list

IDL compiler has an option called --remove-msgs to ignore specified messages
in a given file. This commit adds an option "--remove <remove-list-file>"
to build.sh that passes <remove-list-file> to the IDL compiler script.

This commit incidentally fixes a limitation where if multiple files are
specified as arguments to build.sh, it only passes the last one to IDL
compiler.

Change-Id: I2f87b9ea21d6e0ebf143c55cc3e054f0c3200f2b
commits.subject: QMIIDL-37 - Add build option to disable messages from an input list

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-36 - Fix result TLV type in QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_UIM_SLOT_RESP

Issue Description:
QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_UIM_SLOT_RESP returns incorrect TLV Type '2' for 'multi_sim_mode'.

Root Cause:
In QMI response message, Type 0x02 is reserved by Qualcomm to hold the result codes.
QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_UIM_SLOT_RESP incorrectly use TLV Type '2' for 'multi_sim_mode'

Solution:
Update message struct swi_dms_get_uim_slot_resp_msg in swiqmi_swidms_v01.idl
 - relocate the 'Result Code' as the 2nd parameter. Such that the TLV Type of
   'multi_sim_mode' and 'auto_uim_mode' are shifted down by 1

Resolves: QMIIDL-36
Change-Id: Ie25413ad9f78e42f1db615d30923447dab01745f
Signed-off-by: Ryan Liu <rliu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-36 - Fix result TLV type in QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_UIM_SLOT_RESP

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-24 - QMI support for DSSS (KSIMSEL)

Issue Description:
New feature. Requirement ID: WP76FW-73
Dual SIM Single Standby should be supported when 2 SIMs are connected to
the same physical UIM interface using the modified dev kit with SIM multiplexer

Root Cause:
New feature. Requirement ID: WP76FW-73

Solution:
Create two QMI messages of SWI DMS Service Type Message:
 - QMI_SWI_DMS_SET UIM_SLOT, and
 - QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_UIM_SLOT
The new QNI messages shall support both AT!UIMS and AT+KSIMSEL commands.

Limitations:
At the moment, this ticket will handle +KSIMSEL command only.
For AT!UIMS users, they can stll use the mesages QMI_DMS_SWI_UIM_SELECT
and QMI_DMS_SWI_GET_UIM_SELECTION.

Resolves: QMIIDL-24 QTI9X07-2597
Related: FORE-250
Change-Id: Ibfe08bdd428aa626640f0961616ff56cdc1b74e6
Signed-off-by: Ryan Liu <rliu@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QMIIDL-24 - QMI support for DSSS (KSIMSEL)

commits.commitMessage:
QTI9X05-96 - Crash in dog.c due to watchdog detect qapi_qcci task starvation

Description:
Device crash when power up

Root cause:
Watchdog timeout due to qapi_qcci task stuck in initialiation

Solution:
Lower Sierra QAPI RCINIT priorities;
Enable QAPI/QMIIDL packages;
Decrease heap usage for some items (not related with the crash, should
review/adjust time by time);
Fix some compiling warnings.

Testing:
No crash anymore, AT commands work fine.

Change-Id: I673ac22c208e7d39d8408e604c0934218f4dab9d
Resolves: QTI9X05-96
Signed-off-by: Nancy Yuan <nyuan@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QTI9X05-96 - Crash in dog.c due to watchdog detect qapi_qcci task starvation

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-29 - Add SWI RMS QMI idl define file

Issue Description:
Add SWI RMS QMI commands

Root Cause:
1 Customer will use these two qmi below.
eQMI_RMS_GET_SMS_WAKE = 32,(Get SMS wake settings)
eQMI_RMS_SET_SMS_WAKE (Set SMS wake settings)
2 Provide RMS QMI idl for customer using. 

Solution:
1 Creat RMS QMI idl file
2 Register a QMI service for RMS
3 add RMS qmi test case and test pass

comments.message: QMI_RMS_RESET we do not need in EM9190

Is this ever supported in any product? Do we want to start the trend where a certain QMI message   of a QMI service group would not be implemented whereas the QMI IFS doc still assumes that the message is supported. I always expect that documentation and implementation should match.
yes,no any product use QMI_RMS_RESET.there are many qmis not be implemented in source code whereas the QMI IFS doc still supported,we just add the qmi that we need.

Hi Peter - I'm just confused because the changes didn't show up in the sdx55 project.  Did they not work?  

I'm wondering if the Sierra swiext header file should be included in the Qualcomm header file.  The question is really - what header file should a client or service include in order to use these messages?  If the goal is for the client/service to include the Qualcomm header file and then have access to Qualcomm and swiext messages, like it was before, than we should be including the swiext header in the original qualcomm header files.  If we were doing that, we shouldn't need to extern the object, as far as I can tell.  Can you confirm?

Patch Set 8:

> Patch Set 8:
> 
> Hi Peter - I'm just confused because the changes didn't show up in the sdx55 project.  Did they not work?  
[Shawn:] Since for sdx55 project change dependence for this commit, you can see https://gerrit.legato/q/topic:%22QTIX5510-245%22+(status:open%20OR%20status:merged), if you merged this commit, Xin will merge another two commits.
> 
> I'm wondering if the Sierra swiext header file should be included in the Qualcomm header file.  The question is really - what header file should a client or service include in order to use these messages?  If the goal is for the client/service to include the Qualcomm header file and then have access to Qualcomm and swiext messages, like it was before, than we should be including the swiext header in the original qualcomm header files.  If we were doing that, we shouldn't need to extern the object, as far as I can tell.  Can you confirm?
[Shawn:] 1,client or service should include Qualcomm header, and Qualcomm header should include Sierra swiext header.
2, Since in the Sierra swiext header file, actually didn't extern the object for idl compiler generate the .h file, so we need to modify the build.sh to extern the object after idl compiler generated the .h file, and then in Qualcomm .c file can use it. 

For example:
1) device_management_service_swiext_v01.h:
#define dms_swiext_get_service_object_v01( ) \
          dms_swiext_get_service_object_internal_v01( \
            DMS_SWIEXT_V01_IDL_MAJOR_VERS, DMS_SWIEXT_V01_IDL_MINOR_VERS, \
            DMS_SWIEXT_V01_IDL_TOOL_VERS )
As you know, we call dms_swiext_get_service_object_v01() to get the object before, but dms_swiext_get_service_object_v01() cannot directly be used in dms_qmi_idl_service_object_v01(this is a sturcture variable). and actually it will return dms_swiext_qmi_idl_service_object_v01. dms_swiext_qmi_idl_service_object_v01 doesn't extern in device_management_service_swiext_v01.h after idl compiler generate it, that is why we need to extern it.

2) device_management_service_v01.c :
/*Service Object*/
struct qmi_idl_service_object dms_qmi_idl_service_object_v01 = {
  0x06,
  0x01,
  0x02,
  12311,
  { sizeof(dms_service_command_messages_v01)/sizeof(qmi_idl_service_message_table_entry),
    sizeof(dms_service_response_messages_v01)/sizeof(qmi_idl_service_message_table_entry),
    sizeof(dms_service_indication_messages_v01)/sizeof(qmi_idl_service_message_table_entry) },
  { dms_service_command_messages_v01, dms_service_response_messages_v01, dms_service_indication_messages_v01},
  &dms_qmi_idl_type_table_object_v01,
  0x43,
	
/* SWISTART */
	
#ifdef SIERRA
	
  &dms_swiext_qmi_idl_service_object_v01  //[Shawn:] this object should be externed, otherwise build will fail.
	
#else
  NULL
	
#endif
	
/* SWISTOP */
};

The final problem is that the WDS IDL has a type change.  The previous solution used a "stub" in the sierra-qmi-idl project to ensure the correct type definition was used. It looks like when Qualcomm controls all the IDL, they would put such definitions in a "wds_common" file, to be used by both services. commits.commitMessage:
QTIX5510-245 - Optimize the Sierra QMI Integration Process

Issue Description:
For Sierra extensions of existing Qualcomm services, the previous integration
process required significant scripted manipulation of the generated files to
add offsets to message tables, and then manual integration of those table
entries into the Qualcomm service files.

Solution:
Use Qualcomm's parent service inheritance to integrate the service extensions
by providing only a reference to the Sierra service object.  The impact on this
repository is that the offset manipulation can be removed, and some trivial
manipulation to extern the service objects is added.  The same non-generated
content is observed in Qualcomm service objects, where inheritence is used.

Change-Id: I8023aa9d7be4554d0e672b120c18f48ba45b8714
Signed-off-by: Peter Chen <pechen@sierrawireless.com>
commits.subject: QTIX5510-245 - Optimize the Sierra QMI Integration Process

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-22 - Remove erroneous enum size declaration in OMADM Service

Removed SWIQMI_OMADM_START_SESSION_RSP_WIDTH max size declaration in idl.

The IDL compiler already inserts the 32-bit width declaration during
compilation, so the desired effect is still acheived.  The previous code
triggered the following error when compiled with certain compilers -
specifically the latest RVCT tools for ThreadX on MDM9x05.

Error: #66-D: enumeration value is out of "int" range

Related: SWIMDM-235

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-19 - Add new QMI object for HW watchdog

Add new QMI commands objects to read and write the HW watchdog
parameters in the sysfs.

1) Add new QMI objects to read and write the HW watchdog
   parameters in the sysfs.

- QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_HW_WATCHDOG_REQ
- QMI_SWI_DMS_GET_HW_WATCHDOG_RESP
- QMI_SWI_DMS_SET_HW_WATCHDOG_REQ
- QMI_SWI_DMS_SET_HW_WATCHDOG_RESP

2) Add new QAPI objects so that HW watchdog parameters in sysfs
   can be read/written from MPSS side.

Resolves: QMIIDL-19 QTI9X07-3512
Related: FORE-102
Change-Id: I682272d972e14ab3de13b641a4155b091aee5380
Signed-off-by: Kenneth Cheng <kce@sierrawireless.com>

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-9 - Fix TLV order in QMI_SWILOC_GET_GNSS_PERMITTED_STATE_RESP

This change resolves an incorrect Type value for the gnss_permitted_state TLV
in the QMI_SWILOC_GET_GNSS_PERMITTED_STATE_RESP message.  The order of the
TLV definitions in the IDL definition caused the noted TLV to be added after
the Response (T=0x02) TLV.

The initial implementation of this message was present in EM/MC product lines
prior to the specification review being completed.  The message has not been
implemented in any Smart modules (WP/AR), and has been implemented correctly
in EM/MC source code, while incorrectly in IDL.  There is therefore no
compatibility issue with this fix.

Change-Id: I79edc78974af6e516844423171983db41cc9a4aa
commits.subject: QMIIDL-9 - Fix TLV order in QMI_SWILOC_GET_GNSS_PERMITTED_STATE_RESP

QMIIDL-8 - Update IDL line endings to UNIX format

This change only modifies the line endings in IDL files to use the
UNIX format, whereas they were all previously submitted with DOS
format line endings. The change corresponds to the expected
development environment for the sierra-qmi-idl repository. A
whitespace cleanup script was used previously to use uniform line
endings, but was mistakenly set to conform to DOS format.

The build script is also updated to restore the intended destination
for HTML output, described in ./README.

Generated outputs are all updated, since the inputs are all modified.
There are no functional changes within this change.

Change-Id: I7cd14f0a003ef6a039f537b70d62316678309345

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-5 - Support single IDL compilation

This change adds support to compile a single IDL file, to minimize
changes per review.  Previously all IDL files were compiled on every
execution, which resulted in updated timestamps in all generated files,
making the review more complicated than necessary.  Now the user has
the option of compiling a single IDL file at a time, which removes the
need to review generated output that contains only timestamp changes.

A help menu is added (./build.sh -h) to document the syntax.

A --format option is also added, which modifies IDL files in place
for common formating problems, including use of tabs, DOS line
endings, non-ASCII characters (frequently copied in from the original
specification document), and trailing whitespace.  The IDL has not
been updated to adhere to these rules as part of this change.

The cleanup functionality is improved to include cleanup of the XML
and HTML files.  The generated common_v01 XML and HTML are now
removed from the repository for the same reason the C/H files are
removed post-compilation.

Change-Id: I91f4ba934e88d2c31b285e9c34618ec96fc7c426
commits.subject: QMIIDL-5 - Support single IDL compilation

some has no swi included, e.g qapi_m2m_general_v01.c
some are swi* only, e.g swi_legato_service_v01.c
some uses abbreviation for service, e.g dms; some use full name, e.g device_management_service...

Thanks,
Maggie

Patch Set 2:

Hi Maggie,

Yes, I'd defer that to another ticket, but I agree that the naming is inconsistent and often plain wrong ("qapi" is a poor choice as a prefix, for example - if anything it's swiapi, not "q" api).  The one improvement I did make here was for the Qualcomm services that Sierra extends - they are all now <orig QCT file name>_<extension: eg. swiext>_v01.idl.  

EM/MC is the easy case here, but for WP we have more compatibility constraints, and need to be more cautious with renaming files.  Other system components need to build against these QMI header files, and so changing the names can have impact on those components too.  But if not for this product line, we definitely plan to use better naming for next-gen.  The first two phases of QMIIDL integration were intended to basically centralize the existing solutions, without a major refactoring.  

Thanks,
Ryan

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-2 - Merge support of mdm9x50 Sierra QMI definitions

This change introduces Sierra QMI improvements from the mdm9x50 EM/MC
project.  Key changes include:
  1. Addition of Dying Gasp messages to DMS
  2. New Optional TLVs added to QAPI service FM Operations
  3. SWI LOC Message enumerations corrected to start at 0x0001,
     service IDL file revision increased if backwards compatibility
     is required.
  4. New Optional HTTP status TLV added to QMI_SWI_M2M_AVMS_EVENT_IND
  5. New Optional TLVs added to QMI_SWI_M2M_AVMS_GET_SETTINGS_RESP and
     QMI_SWI_M2M_AVMS_SET_SETTINGS_REQ
  6. SWI NAS service added, and QTI NAS extension service renamed from
     swi_nas (duplicate of the SWI NAS service, 0xFC) to nas_swiext.
  7. Various documentation updates via improved IDL commenting
  8. Various alignment/formatting improvements

Signed-off-by: Ryan Kirk <rkirk@sierrawireless.com>
Change-Id: I618d3cce91f245e55eed5e1ead0d500793e1899b
commits.subject: QMIIDL-2 - Merge support of mdm9x50 Sierra QMI definitions

comments.message: You don't have to do this in this ticket, but just noting that as a future clean-up effort we should look into removing this "Ping" comment from the request definitions. It appears in a lot of files and can be quite misleading.

Patch Set 2:

This still requires a ton of explanation and some cleanup, but in it's current form it's being used with mdm9x07 to remove all the Sierra message definitions from the AMSS project.  Consider this a line in the sand with a day or so of work left, but it's ready to take a look at.  The key things to look at are build.sh, and the IDL files.  Everything else is either pulled in from Qualcomm, or generated.  I prefer to commit the generated h/c to avoid discrepencies in IDL compilers.  I prefer to commit the HTML/XML to avoid testers needing to setup an environment to generate this output.  But all open for debate.

Patch Set 2:

Thanks Ryan. Would it help if we had a readme file in this directory that gives the user some high level instructions on how to navigate/compile the IDL code? Ex: the fact that all changes must go into the IDL first, and what are the commands and tools involved?

Patch Set 2:

For sure, that's part of what I'm planning as "a ton of explanation" :).  Instructions for how to use this will be part of the final commit.

commits.commitMessage:
QMIIDL-1 - Setup common Sierra QMI IDL Repository

Initial population of the Sierra QMI IDL repository, with initial platform
integration testing performed with mdm9x07-based WP76xx, using changes
developed for QTI9X07-833 - Integration of Sierra QMI IDL Repository.

This initial phase development includes proof-of-concept integration with only
a single platform.  This change establishes a basic repository structure and
enables and provides instructions for integration.

Refer to ./README for package details.

Signed-off-by: Ryan Kirk <rkirk@sierrawireless.com>
Change-Id: Ib92f5b018e847ee084be384b5d43f047cde5e0e6

comments.message: We typically have a file header comment. Looks like you put this at line 15?
Can you remove all the tab spacing here and make it more uniform?
What's the reason this error code is defined in the common_v01.idl instead of the wireless_device_service_swiext_v01.idl file?

It's because of the new integration method. To allow us to simply include the Sierra header file, we can't redefine types within it. So we need a declaration of the type, just for name and size, and the content doesn't actually matter here.  We could even remove all the values just to emphasize this.  It's admittedly not ideal, but given that there's one instance of this, it seems like a reasonable cost.
I see, thanks, that's quite a good idea.
Can you remove all the tab spacing here and make it more uniform?
Can remove this part, this service contains a lot more sub-categories now in addition to the highlighted ones.
Since the Legato service is completely managed by the Legato team, does that mean they will be using the IDL file from this project as well?

I'd argue we shouldn't think of it that way anymore.  Legato team "manages" this service through the QMI SME team, same as any team manages any other service - they shouldn't be using different rules.  So all I've done here is taken the IDL from the qmiAirVantage project and bring it here instead.  Once we update the Legato header fetch scripts to use this copy, we should remove the local IDL from that project.  If we never end up doing that, we should still consider this the master for that service, same as all other Sierra QMI services.
Yes, that sounds good to me. I was hoping that they would be on board with this as well.
Should this be updated to QMIIDL-1
